User survey for ImagingSociety 2025 - National MRI research infrastructure in Norway

Author

Dr. Athanasia M. Mowinckel

Published

September 19, 2025

Background

This report presents an analysis of the survey data collected for the national grant scheme application for MRI research infrastructure in Norway. The survey was designed to gather insights from the research community on the current use, needs, and challenges related to MRI for human research.

The following sections will present a summary of the key findings, including graphical representations of the quantitative data and a textual summary of the open-ended responses, with the help of the Gemini LMM.

Survey Results

Of the 33 responses, 12 participants reported they currently use MRI for research, 36% indicate a future interest in using the new MRI facility for their work.

Participant Demographics

This section provides an overview of the survey participants’ roles and institutions.

Research Areas

The survey respondents represent a diverse range of research areas, but cognitive neuroscience is a dominant theme. Many are working directly within cognitive neuroscience, while others are applying cognitive neuroscience principles to specific populations and conditions.

Key areas of focus include:

  • Cognitive Neuroscience: This is the most frequent response, with variations like “cognitive neuroscience of music,” “cognitive neuroscience of language,” and “integrative neuroscience.”
  • Mental Health: Many researchers are studying mental disorders (general, psychotic, mood), psychotherapy, child and adolescent psychiatry, anorexia nervosa, and related areas like brain development and mental health.
  • Aging and Dementia: A significant number are focused on healthy aging, dementia, Alzheimer’s, cerebrovascular disease, and related cognitive decline.
  • Brain Injury: This is a distinct area with focus on brain injury in sport and general brain injury with rehabilitation medicine
  • Neuroscience: Many research areas related to Neuroscience, such as Affective, social and political neuroscience, Epilepsy and multiple sclerosis were also areas focused on by respondents of the survey.

Other notable areas of interest include:

  • Sexual health
  • Women’s health
  • Pain (neurobiology of pain)
  • Autoimmunity
  • Bilingualism
  • Body image
  • Qualitative research
  • Image-based health records and deep learning

How MRI Would Enhance Research

In summary, the survey responses overwhelmingly indicate that increased access to MRI would significantly expand and improve research across a wide range of disciplines. The key themes emerging from the responses are:

  • Essential for Current Research: Many researchers already heavily rely on MRI (both structural and functional) as a primary data acquisition method for their existing projects in areas like neurology, brain stimulation, bilingualism, dementia research, cognitive and emotional processes, and brain function.
  • Expanded Research Possibilities: Easier and more affordable access would unlock new research avenues, including investigations into sexual dysfunction, decision-making, pain, inflammation, and the neurobiology of various conditions like ADHD, SLE, and eating disorders.
  • Improved Research Quality and Scope: Better access would lead to larger participant samples, enhanced study designs, and more reliable data, allowing researchers to conduct more well-powered and impactful investigations. High-performance fMRI was specifically mentioned as a beneficial advancement.
  • Facilitation of Collaboration: Increased access would enable participation in multi-center studies, fostering collaboration across institutions and allowing for larger, more diverse datasets and contributing to the advancement of the field.
  • Accessibility for Patients: Access to research MRIs would allow for participants with conditions such as concussion, eating and neurodevelopmental disorders to be more easily be recruited into the research.
  • Overcoming Current Limitations: The lack of access to MRI is a major constraint, forcing researchers to collect data externally (even internationally) or limiting the scope of their studies. Improved access would address this bottleneck.
  • Clinical Applications: MRI provides clinically relevant information for decision making, tracking of disease progression and the development of novel algorithms that can be tested and validated in a hospital setting.
  • Organizational Models: A model where the management of the scanner would be possible with trained scientists (like in the intervention center) and it would not depend on a monetary model.
  • Neuroradiologist Availability: The lack of neuroradiologists for clinical assessments is a current limitation.

Future Needs

This section analyzes which conditions are considered most important for the future of MRI research in Norway.

Summary of Free-text Comments

This section provides a summary of the open-ended comments, generated using the Gemini LMM.

Survey respondents highlighted the need for expanded MRI research capabilities, with a particular emphasis on resources independent from clinical demands. Concerns were raised about the existing allocation of resources, suggesting a desire for prioritizing research access and potentially lower costs. Beyond physical resources, respondents also expressed a strong interest in fostering a collaborative MRI research community, specifically mentioning the need for such a network in Tromsø.

Conclusion

In conclusion, this survey resoundingly underscores the urgent need for increased access to dedicated research-focused MRI scanners within Norway. The compelling narratives shared by researchers across diverse institutions and disciplines highlight how limited access currently hinders innovative studies, restricts sample sizes, and impedes collaboration. While some researchers have found alternative solutions, such as international collaborations or utilizing clinical scanners, these are often suboptimal and unsustainable. The strong support for investment in research MRI infrastructure, coupled with specific suggestions for improvements like collaborative communities and prioritizing research over clinical use, provides a clear roadmap for policymakers and funding bodies. Investing in dedicated research MRI scanners is not merely an expenditure; it is a strategic investment in the future of Norwegian research, with the potential to unlock breakthroughs in understanding and treating a wide range of conditions, from neurological disorders and mental health challenges to chronic pain and age-related cognitive decline. Ultimately, providing researchers with the tools they need will empower them to advance scientific knowledge, improve patient outcomes, and solidify Norway’s position as a leader in cutting-edge biomedical research.
